ce. Some of these poems are by men and a few by women (including the trobairitz); many are anonymous, and often the gender of the poet is unresolvable. A "woman's song" in this sense can be defined as a female-voice poem on the subject of love, typically characterized by simple language, sexual candor, and apparent artlessness.The chapters in Medieval Woman's Song bring together scholars in a range of disciplines to examine how both men and women contributed to this art form. Without eschewing consideration of authorship, the collection deliberately overturns the long-standing scholarly practice of treating as separate and distinct entities female-voice lyrics composed by men and those composed by women. What is at stake here is less the voice of women themselves than its cultural and generic construction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aVocal musicy15th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aVocal musicy500-1400xHistory and criticism. 0aWomen musicians. 0aWomen singers. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aGender Studies.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aWomen's Studies.1 aBelanoff, Pat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennett, Judith M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoynton, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBums, E. Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Judith R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorral, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKasten, Ingrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlinck, Anne L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlinck, Anne L., e